`template/` is the file scaffold this repo hands to consumers when bootstrapping a new Rust project: a virtual Cargo workspace plus every governance file needed to make strict lints, formatting, licensing, and CI checks non-optional from the first commit. Nothing here is itself part of the ctx-context tool; depending on this directory means copying its contents into a fresh repo as-is.

The quality-gate configs are layered and must be kept mutually consistent: `Cargo.toml` sets workspace-level hard-deny lints (unsafe forbidden, unwrap/expect/panic denied, warnings denied) but they're inert until each member crate adds `[lints] workspace = true` — currently no members are listed, so this is inactive until a real crate is added. `clippy.toml` sets the two thresholds clippy can enforce natively (80-line functions, 25 cognitive complexity) as hard fails; the tighter soft-tier thresholds it documents (30 lines, complexity 15) are enforced only by `scripts/rationale_check.py` and a not-yet-existing dylint crate, so those three sources drift independently unless someone tracks them by hand. `rust-toolchain.toml` pins Rust 1.95.0 stable with rustfmt+clippy components; `rustfmt.toml` is valid only for stable-channel rustfmt matching that pin — bumping the toolchain requires re-verifying rustfmt.toml's "no silently-ignored nightly options" claim. `deny.toml` independently governs the dependency graph (crates.io-only, license allowlist, no wildcards/duplicates), orthogonal to the lint stack.

`scripts/` is the single execution path tying these configs together — `ci.sh` is the one entry point that runs formatting, clippy, docs, dependency, and rationale checks and is what `.github/`'s CI workflow invokes. `.claude/` and `.gitattributes` are unrelated tooling concerns: the former wires Claude Code hooks to a locally-built `ctx-context` debug binary (also built by `scripts/install-tools.sh`, so those two must stay path-compatible), the latter declares a `ctx-regenerate` git merge driver for `.ctx`/rollup files that has no backing implementation yet, meaning merge conflicts in `.context/` must currently be resolved manually.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory, so no divergence can be assessed against it.